{
  "texts": [
    "SAFETY CHIP [62] adds a layer of safety to LLM-based decisions in robotics.Dynamic Knowledge Fusion methods, such as the Two-Tower Architecture [63], process text and KG data separately, while advanced models like KagNet [64] and MHGRN [65] incorporate KG data into the text, and GreaseLM [66] and QA-GNN [67] introduce deep interaction mechanisms.Our approach integrates LLMs with Embodied Robotic Control Prompts (ERCPs) and an Embodied Knowledge Graph (EKG), utilizing Neo4j [68] and Cypher queries [69] for efficient data management.",
    "A Graph Attention Network (GAT) model computes attention weights for critical nodes in the EKG, guiding task plan validation.",
    "Hamiltonian Paths ensure the correct sequence of critical nodes during execution.This integration is formulated as a multi-stage optimization problem: S = arg max P∈T F(P, K EKG, P ERCP), where:• P: A candidate task plan, • T: The space of possible plans, • K EKG: Knowledge from the EKG, represented as a graph G = (V, E), with entities V and relationships E, • P ERCP: A combination of user instructions, action primitives, and clarifications, formalized as P ERCP = {c, A, T }, where c is the user command, A is the action set, and T represents textual clarifications.",
    "The objective function F evaluates the feasibility and safety of the plan:F(P, K EKG, P ERCP) = a∈P V(a, K EKG, P ERCP),where V(a, K EKG, P ERCP) is a validation function that checks if action a meets safety and feasibility criteria:V(a, K EKG, P ERCP) =1 if a is safe and feasible, 0 otherwise.To ensure the correct sequence of visits, a Hamiltonian Path constraint is added:H(P, K EKG) =1 if P visits all critical nodes in order, 0 otherwise.The validated task plan S is determined by solving the constrained optimization problem: S = arg max P∈T F(P, K EKG, P ERCP) subject to H(P, K EKG) = 1.TABLE I: Comparative Analysis of Key Features: Knowledge Graphs as a Knowledge Base, Operation in Unseen Environments, Plan Visualization and Correction, Plan Optimization, and Safety Evaluation â ȂŤ Our Approach vs. Related Works KG as KB Unseen Env.",
    "Safety Eval.CodeBotler [45] x -✓ ✓ ✓ x ProgPrompt [47] x ✓ ✓ ✓ x xCode as Policies [48] x✓ ✓ ✓ ✓ x REFLECT [50] x - ✓ ✓ x xToT [58] x✓ ✓ ✓ ✓ x Safety Chip [62] x - x x x ✓ Ours ✓ ✓ ✓ ✓ ✓ ✓ III."
